product_name: Logitech H390 Wired Headset, Stereo Headphones with Noise-Cancelling Microphone, USB, In-Line Controls, PC/Mac/Laptop - Black
review_header: Horrible- time and frustration not worth the money
review_text: I bought these headphones as part of a Christmas gift, which was Rosetta Stone. I ordered two sets for me and my significant other to use with the program, and they were sent alone in a box in bags- no instructions on how to use, install, or troubleshoot. I just spent the past three hours trying to figure out how to make these headphones work with two different computers, and ended with the conclusion that they are defective. I have consulted the product website, as well as other FAQs online. I worked with both a PC and Mac; the device was recognized (no problem there at all), and was good to go as part of both computers (green check marks and everything). But when I go to use the actual headphones, the microphone works and can recognize my speech, but the headphones do not at all. I don't hear anything at all, no crackling or faint sound (and no, the headset is not muted on the cord). This has been extremely frustrating, especially considering no instructions were sent with the headsets initially. Even the instructions online were thoroughly unhelpful beyond initial set up.In addition to my horrible experience installing and using the headset, the headset itself is not very comfortable at all, as the name might suggest. The ear pads are very small, so unlike other earphones that I have had before that encompass the entire ear for comfort, these just sit on top and add extra weight. After a few minutes, my ears were already a little tender. Especially with a program like Rosetta Stone, I was looking for a headset I could use for a decent amount of time, and again was disappointed. I would definitely invest in a more quality headset, or a more quality company.

product_name: MUSICOZY White Noise Sleep Headphones, Bluetooth Sleep Mask 3D Wireless Music Sleeping Headphones Earbuds for Insomnia Yoga Travel Office Relax Cool Tech Gadgets Gifts
review_text: So, I‚Äôve only Used a mask to sleep with once because it was a terrible experience- the pressure on my eyes from it caused me not to be able to see things for hours after I took it off. So, for years, I‚Äôve drugged myself instead of using a mask (legally). I saw this on my Amazon home page and it looked like it was selling a dream, but I thought I‚Äôd try to give it a shot, and maybe be able to actually dream with it. Here is my experience with it so far (I‚Äôve had it for about a week). I was super skeptical when I first tried it. I thought the Bluetooth and sound stuff was going to be complicated. But, I literally just hit the power button and it synced to my phone super easy, and the sound was great. I‚Äôm a side sleeper, and I have trigeminal Neuralgia, which makes anything putting pressure on or around my ear excruciating. But, once I moved the speakers where I wanted them, I hardly felt them at all -on a firm pillow, I sort of felt them, on a fluffy pillow, I didn‚Äôt feel them at all. Additionally, there‚Äôs a ton of room between the mask and my eyes. As far as light leakage, I read some of the reviews before I bought this and someone mentioned they had a little. But, for me, even when I‚Äôm broad daylight, it‚Äôs literally light‚Äôs out -which kind of makes it hard when you wake up in the morning and the sun is suddenly blasting in your face. But, for falling asleep, amazing. So, maybe depending  on peoples facial structure there could be light leakage where you may just have to adjust the mask a bit to avoid that. But, wasn‚Äôt for me (I have a long, narrow sort of face). Here are some things to watch out for: if you have strap on too tight, you might feel where the buttons are on the front of the mask and get a headache. -I did. But, then I just loosened the strap just a little and everything was fine (even with the strap a tad loose, I had no light leakage). One other thing is that I have no idea how long the battery lasts. I sleep about 8 hours, sometimes less, sometimes more. Haven‚Äôt had any issues so far there. But, I don‚Äôt know what happens when the battery starts to get old or how long it would take for the battery to get old. I hope this review is helpful!

product_name: Sony WH-1000XM4 Wireless Premium Noise Canceling Overhead Headphones with Mic for Phone-Call and Alexa Voice Control, Black
review_header: Pairing Not Easy, No Soundstage like XM3s, Excellent Battery Life
review_text: Tried these out from a relative who likes them but I was not overly impressed.  While having a few features the XM3s do not have, these are very touchy in terms of controls...swiping and at times even pairing.  Sony's decision not to allow a surround sound/virtual stage element to me was a major disappointment.  On the plus side, the headphones do fit better on the head and are comfortable, thanks to the larger earcups too.  I guess since these are similarly-priced to the XM3s, the decision has to be what is more important...some added features and good battery life, or the presence missing with the lack of a virtual stage presence we see in the XM3s.  Unlike the Bose 700/QC35II, these Sony phones have about 50% more hours of battery life per charge.  They are also more comfortable than the XM3s due to bigger earcups.  I currently like my Bose QC25s as you don't need to deal with rechargeable batteries, but when they break, I would consider this one, espcially if the Sony WH1000XM3 is no longer available.  And I read that Sony may change the swipe feature for volume, or improve it, with a dedicated button in the XM5s, but I don't really know if they're that far into the XM5 planning cycle.Update:  June 4, 2022.  Having received the XM5 as a birthday gift from my kids, I've increased the rating on these XM4s.  They are clearly superior over the XM5s.  Lower price, easy foldability, less plastiky, no fingerprint smudges, and a more comfortable headband make the XM4s the better option, while still providing outstanding sound and NC.

review_header: Great headphones for the price, with incredible support and warranty.
review_text: This is my second purchase from OneOdio, and I'm again very satisfied with my purchase. Inside the box is the headphones in a high-quality artificial leather bag, 3 cables, the instruction manual, and the warranty card. There were two audio cables, one of them for use with regular electronic devices, and the other for DJ equipment, and one charging cable, all surprisingly high quality and durable. The warranty card instructs you on how to claim your "2 years warranty", and went over their services-- "30 days of free shipping", "Get a new product for your reasons", and "Solve the problem at any time". I've already registered my product for the warranty, and it was very simple. The headphones have rich bass, and great sound quality. They have a great design, and are incredibly comfortable to wear. However, about a week ago, my headphones unexpectedly broke when I picked them up to put them on. The connector that helps the headphones swivel broke, and I couldn't put it back together. I was skeptical about the "2 years warranty" at first, but it turned out to be great. OneOdio responded to me within a day after my inquiry on the warranty, and asked me to send a picture or video of my issue. After sending them a picture of my issue, they emailed me and told me that they were going to ship me a new pair. I was very impressed with the support. If you are skeptical about these headphones, don't worry, because you can just claim your warranty if you dislike them or they break. Even though they broke for me, I think it's pretty unlikely to happen again. In conclusion, if you want good, comfortable headphones for under $60, these are a great option!

review_header: The sound quality is excellent with large range and bass !!!
review_text: Today 4-21-2021 I received the TOZO NC2. I am speechless the NC2 are great earbuds, the sound clarity is so amazing it feels like you just got a $200 product. Everything is so amazing about the NC2, from the unboxing, the manual, the quick pairing with your device, man it is so easy and so simple my grandma can do it. The excellence, the quality, and the sound of the earbuds are so great, you have to try to see what it feels like. Unbelievable sound quality, clarity, and perfection. Not surprised TOZO is an amazing company that delivers outstanding products and excellence in everything they do.The build quality is excellent, the case feels pleasant to the touch and has an addictive snapping action. The headphone nubs are very comfortable, and a wide range of sizes are offered which was helpful for me as I have big ears. The headphones stay in no problem, and the no button touch sensor is a definite upgrade compared to the otherwise loud button clicking.The sound quality is likewise good with a large range and bass that you might find in some full on-ear headsets. The battery life is great too, I've yet to find myself out of juice. Overall, I think TOZO really knocked it out of the park with these headphones!Thank you very much for your great products great quality and price!!!

product_name: Sennheiser Professional HD 280 PRO Over-Ear Monitoring Headphones
review_text:
I was gifted a pair of these headphones by my girlfriend about 2 years ago. Before that I owned a pair of HD448's, which broke when I accidentally crushed them in my backpack, and then a pair of HD449's, until my rabbit bit the cord in two. I was initially excited when I received these. I had tried several brands of headphones including AKG's, Sony's, and Audio-Technica's, but I had always thought my cheap Sennheiser's sounded better. These headphones, being Sennies, would be just as good, I assumed. I can't easily convey you the disappointment I felt when I listened to the first track with the HD280's. A good analogy might be going to a restaurant for the first time that everyone says is good, but is honestly mediocre, like Olive Garden. The difference being that you have to stand that disappointment every time you listen to music, not just when your friends drag you there for endless breadsticks. I kept a smile on my face for an entire song to please my girlfriend, but I was just hoping all the while that it was only an effect of not being properly broken in. That was not the case, they did not get better, or grow on me.These headphones have bass, a very flabby and undefined bass. People complain about the cheap Sennheiser's for the same reason, but I can guarantee that these headphones are worse in that regard. Sennheiser's are known for their high-end detail, but these have none. The sound is balanced, but un-nuanced, totally cheap, like they are being driven by weak magnets. I honestly believe these are $50 headphones that Sennheiser stuck their name on and up-charged $50. When doing a head-to-head with these headphones vs. the Sony MDR-v6's I got my girlfriend, I'd choose the Sony's, and they are $60 new. The sound isolation is great, probably a bit better than the HD449's I had. It accomplishes this by squeezing your head so tight you might think it would burst. I can only comfortably wear these for about an hour and a half at a time.Instead of spending the entire review complaining about these headphones, I will offer a solution. For the EXACT SAME PRICE, you can buy the entry level *real* Sennheiser's, the¬†
  
HD449







  
  
    ¬†(or whatever is in it's place by the time you read this comment). With the HD449's you get an overall clearer and more detailed sound and are more comfortable to wear. Personally, my next headphone will be an¬†
  
HD598 Cs Closed Back







  
  
    , which I will pair with a DAC+Amp for dedicated listening, while the lower impedance should allow me to run them without an amp on a mobile device.

product_name: Bose QuietComfort 45 Bluetooth Wireless Noise Cancelling Headphones - Triple Black
review_header: Unfathomably comfortable but lacking in a few areas
review_text: First things first, I can't complain too much because I've never had a pair of headphones that fit me so well that I don't feel them at all. My ears aren't big top to bottom but they stick out far from my head which has limited my brands to Sennheiser and Bose only so far. These have strategically placed drivers that don't make contact with my ears at all, which even Sennheiser falls short of.Now the bad stuff:There's no passive mode for noise cancellation. It's either "aware" where it pipes through sound picked up by the mic or "quiet" which is your (admittedly very good) active noise cancellation. Having no passive means that if you're performing any tasks that produce sharp noises like snapping twigs, chopping wood, even cooking with a loud pop coming from the pan, the microphone won't be able to keep up and you'll get an extremely uncomfortable pressure and additional, millisecond delayed pop or snap coming from the headphones themselves.If you're driving on a loud road(and I assume flying as well) the noise cancellation will need to ramp up to compensate and while better than many other brands, the pressure on your ears can become intense and uncomfortable.If you're lying on your side, head on pillow and you put a little too much weight on the headphones, the drivers (and hence the fancy destructive interference waves from the active noise cancellation) get just a little too close to function properly and start ringing with a pitch like a smoke alarm. To get the full effect, you really must try it right as you're about to fall asleep, letting your head finally relax from the long day's stress.All of those faults could be fixed with a passive mode that does not at the time of writing this exist.As for the sound:It's fine. The bass is there and totally loud enough but not super punchy or well defined. The mids and highs are likewise fine. No complaints exactly but somehow Bose managed to strip the joy out of a lot of listening experiences. Excellent compromise I guess. And the longer I listen, the less I'm annoyed by what's lacking. But it still never makes me go, "Agh I freaking love this [solo/bass line/singer/audiobook narrator]!"These headphones are solidly four stars but keep in mind that's 4.0 not 4.1

review_header: Fourth time I've bought these. Take from that what you will.
review_text: This is the fourth set I've bought, albeit under four different "brands"; whoever manufactures these keeps changing the name and the color scheme, but they're the same thing, from the "your headset is connected" voice to the little circular case they come in. Each one lasts about six months, or probably about 300 hours of play time. The sound quality is fine, but a real audiophile would probably want something more. They're comfy enough to wear while sleeping; I use them primarily to listen to music, audiobooks, or podcasts as I fall asleep. The battery life is pretty good. I only have to charge them every other day or so, though again, I don't use them very heavily. Each previous set I've had has lasted about six months, and then they don't charge, they randomly turn on and off, or they just stop working altogether. At this price, six months of life is acceptable for me. Would it be better if they lasted longer? Of course. But these days, unfortunately, we live in a world of disposable electronics.

product_name: TOZO T10 Bluetooth 5.3 Wireless Earbuds with Wireless Charging Case IPX8 Waterproof Stereo Headphones in Ear Built in Mic Headset Premium Sound with Deep Bass for Sport Black (2022 Upgraded)
review_text: Reasons why I returned mine:- Flashing blue light on the side when on - I only noticed these when I was using them at night and saw my room being lit up at about a 5 second interval. Because the two buds are not paired at the same time, the buds flash independent of one another (not at the same time). I prefer something more subtle and would rather not piss off someone I'm sitting next to when on the plane or train.- Voice over is annoying. On removal of the buds from the charging case, there will be a woman's voice saying that the device has been turned on, right ear connected, left ear connected, etc. Similarly, when turning the devices on/off manually by holding the button on the side, it'll beep and say device on/off. Superunnecessary, things like this should be seamless - just remove it from the case and start the music.- Connection drops out - over the course of about an hour and half walking throughout NYC, the connection dropped off two times. It managed to auto-fix itself without having to do anything, but still a slight annoyance.- No volume control on the buds themselves.- Not too fond of the fit despite trying all bud shapes. You're supposed to turn these at an angle toward the back of the ear but it still didn't feel that secure. It fell out once when walking as I raised my arm and brushed my ear lightly. I can't really compare it to other wireless buds as this was my first pair. The standard corded apple earbuds are still my go to.Good points:- It'll last at least 2 hours per charge as I haven't tested it for longer.- Call quality/mic seem to be okay. I've only tested them with ~a minute long call.

review_header: Great purchase, sound great, amazingly comfortable
review_text: I have owned these headphones for about 2.5 months now and have used them for multiple hours each day listening to music with the noise cancellation on outside, in my living room and in the garage doing woodworking. The sound quality of the music is amazing and the noise cancelling is on point. I use them with music and noise cancelling as my hearing protection when sanding and using power tools. I can barely hear the tools when I have them on. They are the most comfortable over the ear headphones I have ever owned (and I‚Äôve owned quite a few). I have big ears and these completely cover them with zero pressure on any part of my ear or head. I think I‚Äôve charged the headphones 3 times in the last 2.5 months. The battery life is as amazing as the comfort. I haven‚Äôt travelled with them so I don‚Äôt know how they do on planes, but they block out the barking of my 3 dogs really well. I can‚Äôt compare the to the Sony, Bose, or other more expensive brands as I‚Äôve never used their over the ear noise cancelling headphones. I do own the Bose Soundsport in ear headphones and I have to say that I enjoy the soundstage on this headphone than on the Bose. Overall, I got exactly what I was looking for with these headphones.

review_header: How to know if EarPods are original and authentic?
review_text: EarPods are probably the most knocked off accessories on the market and we almost always get fake ones!There are many aspects to test for original EarPods from Apple. The simplest test is to press the buttons on the volume/mic controls. - if you hear loud clicking noises audible a few feet away, they are fake! The authentic, genuine, original EarPods click sounds are soft and barely audible (high quality buttons from Apple).But here is the news - even the original EarPods are not the best in sound quality. You will not hear all the sounds in a song clearly on original EarPods (you will realize this after you try a higher quality headphones). With fake EarPods, the sound quality is even worse!!

review_header: 1 year into owning: Good for daily use.
review_text: Overall these headphones had a great lifespan. I use them daily for gaming - Discord calls and general streaming purposes. They have lasted much longer than many other pairs I have had and having the duel audio jacks proved very helpful for different situations. I used an inline mic for about 6 months while using these and had some audio issues with the one provided (crackle feedback). I found replacements online that lasted maybe 2 months each and eventually switched over to a sepertate mic setup. I now only use the 1/4 audio cable with no issue what-so-ever with sound. Overall the experience was great for being bought way back in May of 2020. Only gripe now (Jan 2022) is the plastic hinge that offers a rotation for 'DJ mode' has essentially given out and can now spin a free 360. This wouldn't be an issue if the headphones did not rely on this for support on the head but now the right headphone is slightly lifted off the bottom of the ear during use. Other than that the 'leather' ear cushions started to fray about 8-9 months after buying. Still comfortable but definitely not stylish. I recommend these if you are planning on using them for anything from everyday to sparingly as they seem to last in terms of audio quality and cord lifespan (1/4 jack). I will most likely be repurchasing these to just refresh the look and have the original comfortable fit it provided.

review_header: Fantastic value, don't hesitate to buy!!
review_text: Where to start?Packaging is excellent, way better than I expected for the price I paid! Clear instructions. The extra rubber pieces for the speakers came in a nice case which is refreshing. Other usually came in a plastic bag and got lost. Charging cable was in a nice box. Definitely an A+ for packaging!The charging case was at 50% so I plugged it in to get 100%, I went to the store and was back in about an hour and it was fully charged and ready for use.I took out them out of the case and they paired to each other in a few seconds. I was then able to pair to my S20. Total time less than 30 seconds, ready to go!The fit was perfect for me so I simply put in and opened Pandora. BAM! Music was booming, excellent sound, not to much bass, great balance.Noise canceling seems about right and battery life was excellent.Oh, phone calls! Sound was good, not as good as when using the phone itself sadly. I was surprised considering the excellent music sound quality. This is NOT a negative at all, just surprised me is all.I did like that when you end a call the music doesn't come back at full volume, ramps back up to it in about a second.  Really appreciate thus feature!!

product_name: Panasonic ErgoFit In-Ear Earbud Headphones RP-HJE120-D (Orange) Dynamic Crystal Clear Sound, Ergonomic Comfort-Fit
review_header: Great headphones even if they were more expensive
review_text: I bought these headphones and just got them earlier today. So far I am very impressed. For the price of $5 it would be VERY difficult to find another pair of earbuds that sound as good as these. That said, don't expect anything too amazing from them, but don't expect too little either. After listening to a lot of songs, all of which have moderate bass I can tell you that they sound very good. The bass is pretty solid too, unless you want to feel your ears reverberating. You can notice the bass, and feel a tiny bit of reverberation, but not a whole lot. But the bass is noticeable.One very important thing about these headphones is that they are very good at canceling noise. Listening to music at a medium level it was hard for me to hear when someone 5 feet away from me would say something in a normal voice. The only thing even remotely close to a complaint with these earbuds is the quality of the cord. It feels relatively cheep and there's nothing to slide up and down to prevent the earbuds from tangling. That said, it's a very minor complaint, and for $5 earbuds I really don't care very much. I definitely do not regret getting these earbuds and would recommend them for anyone looking for a good pair of earbuds for not much money. That said, if you're someone who wants or expects high quality sound with great bass these probably aren't for you; but for earbuds on a budget they're great!

It doesn't make them "squeeze" hour head less.

product_name: Sennheiser Professional HD 280 PRO Over-Ear Monitoring Headphones
review_header: Incredible sound, long life - Updated December 2015
review_text: I've had a pair of these beasts for more than two years now and I've never had a better set of 'phones sonically.Like a number of other people, I find the plastic cover of the headband is cracking and shedding pieces to the point now where it looks like I use the headphones to drive nails.Apparently the outer shell just does not flex enough and I do have a somewhat larger than average head.  It's annoying and looks awful but until they actually fall apart I'll keep using them and then will probably buy another set.Sonically, they are simply incredible.  I use a small portable CD player and it drives them just fine, even on battery power.The noise isolation is wonderful, I use these on airplane trips and most of the noise just vanishes, at home, I often don't hear the telephone ringing on the end table next to me and I don't listen to particularly loud music.  I can enjoy quiet music while my wife watches TV 6' away and barely register that it is on.Every time I play a CD for the first time using these 'phones, I am usually astounded, especially if I've heard the music before on lesser systems. It's like hearing it for the first time.  The depth and clarity simply delight me and I am constantly hearing new things or nuances in the music, even on discs I have heard a hundred times before.The bass is full and rich without sounding like you've plugged your speakers directly into a 60hz AC outlet. (Which seems to be a popular thing to do judging from what some people call "bass" but which is more like the sound made when a brontosauraus has really bad gas.)  Highs are crisp and clear without sounding tinny or ringing and the soundstage is just right at least for me.I use these primarily for classical, jazz and new age/ambient with occasional excursions into classic rock and they just simply work.  I can't comment on how they sound with "rap" or similar noise as I only use these to listen to real music, not someone screaming vulgar words while thumping on a bass drum, but I digress.If you want quality sound with great isolation, buy these, just don't wear them while bicycling or driving, OK?  You won't hear the semi-truck coming through your windshield.;)Update:  In late 2007 I bought another pair of these.  I think they may have solved the cracking headband issue.  I use them almost daily often for two or three hours at a time and the new set does not seem to be showing any signs of the older pair's issues.  Sound quality is still the best I've heard, especially for the money.  They are heavy and a bit hot and the cups could be a bit deeper...they press on my ears a bit after long wear but I've yet to find anything else I like as much.Update to the update:  July 2009.  Still use them heavily almost every day.  Headband is fine, no noticeable wear, cracking or other issues.  I think Sennheiser listened to people.Buy these 'phones!  I've used them now with almost every decent portable music player around, my PC and my stereo.  They just sound good and they keep sounding good.Update cubed - Late May 2011  Still using the same 'phones.  No cracking of headband, no loss of quality.  Only noticeable degradation is that the ear cushions have gotten a bit squishy.  I think they are user replaceable.  I wear these things a good ten hours a week.  I really cannot say enough good things about this product.  There are still companies that know how to make a quality product and offer it at a fair price.Update the 4th - Late in 2012, the ear cushions pretty much gave up the ghost and these things became very uncomfortable to wear.I was going to pitch them and get something newer when I ran a cross a "how to" video from Sennheiser on how to replace the ear cushions.  Turns out to be reasonably easy...watch the video a couple of times as the tech kind of gets his hands in the way in a critical shot or two.  You don't need any tools, just some patience and a willingness to stretch the cushions farther than you think they will stretch.So, I located a (non-Amazom, they didn't have them) source, ordered a set of cushions and once I got them installed (maybe ten minutes work and some cursing as this kind of manual dexterity has never been my long suit), I now have a practically new set of phones that just keep on working.  The headband cushion could use replacing but it's not critical so I am not going to bother.  Cost of the ear cushions was in the mid $20 range, so if they last as long as the original set (and they feel of similar quality, I should be updating this in another four or five years.  :0Update the Fifth - End of December. 2015  Replacement ear pads have held up nicely.  All aspects of the headphone are fine except the strain relief connection where the cord joins the plug has frayed away and it only hangs on by the actual wiring and I expect that to go sooner rather than later and it is NOT user replaceable.That will end my long and lovely relationship with these 'phones.I find I rarely use them now as I obtained a gorgeous pair of Phillips Fidelio headphones earlier in 2015 and they just keep growing on me for any use that does not require the solid sound isolation these provide.But I have gotten more than my money's worth out of the Sennheisers.  Highly recommended.

review_header: As described, increased inner ear pressure when both earbuds are inserted due to snug fit.
review_text: I purchased these for a three year old and a six year old. They are too big for the three year old, and almost perfect for a six year old. But I can't take too many stars off for those reasons since it isn't adverstised as a product for children. They do fit, and they are inserted into the ear canal. The drawback to that is that they can cause internal pressure changes, especially for people with chronic sinus issues, or for those prone to ear infections/sinus infections. We use them in short intervals to mitigate this issue, but next time I think I will go with something that has an over the ear attachment-not only because younger children could use it, but because we all suffer from chronic allergies and the increase in pressure is very uncomfortable when both earbuds are in.

product_name: Audio-Technica ATH-M40x Professional Studio Monitor Headphone, Black, with Cutting Edge Engineering, 90 Degree Swiveling Earcups, Pro-grade Earpads/Headband, Detachable Cables Included
review_text: I ordered these to compare with my Philips Fidelio X2HR's. I wanted a closed back to use in situations where the open back X2HR's would be too loud for others nearby. The first thing I noticed when I unboxed them was they are smaller than the Fidelio's, especially the pads. These are more like on ears than over ears. I don't have a big giant head but man these things are small. I can fall asleep with my Philips on and not be bothered but these are going to take some modding to get them comfortable. I was tempted to just pack 'em up and send 'em back, then I plugged them into my Monolith Liquid Spark and ran a few tunes through them. Sweet. Great staging, nice bass, mids and highs are not fatiguing. The bass on The Grateful Dead's "Box of Rain" is punchy and deep without crapping out so that's a good sign. So it's back to Amazon for some Brainwavez pads to see it that alleviates the insane clamping pressure.

product_name: OneOdio Wired Over Ear Headphones Hi-Res Studio Monitor & Mixing DJ Stereo Headsets with 50mm Neodymium Drivers and 1/4 to 3.5mm Audio Jack for AMP Computer Recording Phone Piano Guitar Laptop - Black
review_text: For the price, I did not expect fantastic sound from these headphones, but from the reviews, I expected halfway decent sound.These headphones are touted as helping you hear the bass better.  I like bass, and I can hear it, along with hissing and distortion to an overall deeper sound.  And when I'm listening to people talking or singing, they sound like they're singing or talking through a can.  Nothing sounds right, and I've run through everything from Adagio for Strings to Comfortably Numb.I'm not kidding:  You can get better sound from a ten dollar pair of headphones, so please don't buy them.  I'm stuck with these till I get something better, which shouldn't be difficult.  The packaging included a card from the manufacturer requesting a review, and I think people tried to be kind and post something nice, and that's why these headphones are so highly rated.  I'm not an expert on headphones, but I know what sounds bad.  Please just don't, because the sound quality is so poor, I feel like I'm going crazy listening to them.They look nice, but are not comfortable, either.  They are adjustable, but they're made from hard, cheap plastic that doesn't give.  They squeeze my head and I've got headaches from them.  I'm just flat embarrassed I'm going to have to tell my husband I'll be buying yet another pair of headphones - not this brand.
